SST
# SST
sst<-read.csv(here::here('data/sst/sst_ts_gtf_strata.csv'))
# SST with season lag
sst.lag <- sst %>%
  arrange(year, month) %>%
  mutate(
         sst_lag12 = lag(weighted_mean_sst,12))
         
# Join with recruit estimate
df <- dplyr::full_join(recruit, sst.lag %>%
                   group_by(year) %>% 
                   filter(year %in% c(2000:2020)),
dplyr::select(year, month, recruit.est, mean_sst, weighted_mean_sst, sst_lag3, sst_lag6, sst_lag9, sst_lag12),
                 by = join_by(year))
sst.rec <- df[-c(1:29),] #removes year < 2000 (when SST data begins)

Here we have SST in recruitment year - by month (updated 12/19)

df = sst.rec %>% 
  mutate(season = case_when(month %in% c(1,2,3) ~ 'winter', 
                            month %in% c(4,5,6) ~ 'spring', 
                            month %in% c(7,8,9) ~ 'summer', 
                            month %in% c(10,11,12) ~ 'fall'),
         strong_year_class = case_when(year %in% c(2005,2013,2017) ~ 'yes',
                                  year %in% c(2000,2006,2014,2018) ~ 'year after',
                                  year %in% c(2001:2004,2007:2012,2015:2016,2019:2020) ~ 'no'))


df %>% group_by(year, season, strong_year_class) %>%
  summarize(sst = mean(weighted_mean_sst),
            r = mean(recruit_est)) %>%
  ggscatter(x = "sst", y = "r",
            add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, 
            color = "strong_year_class", palette = c("black", "green", "red"),
            cor.coef = TRUE, cor.coeff.args = list(method="pearson"),
            add.params=list(color="dodgerblue", fill="lightgray"),
            xlab = "Mean Sea Surface Temperature", ylab = "Recruitment Estimate",
            title="Recruitment year - no lag") +
  facet_wrap(~season, scales = 'free')

Here we have SST lagged by 1 year - by season

df %>% group_by(year, season, strong_year_class) %>% 
  summarize(sst = mean(sst_lag12),
            r = mean(recruit_est)) %>% 
  ggscatter(x = "sst", y = "r", 
            add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, 
            color = "strong_year_class", palette = c("black", "green", "red"),
            cor.coef = TRUE, cor.coeff.args = list(method="pearson"),
            add.params=list(color="dodgerblue", fill="lightgray"),
            xlab = "Mean sea surface temperature", ylab = "Recruitment Estimate",
            title="Lag one year")+
  facet_wrap(~season, scales = 'free')

Cold pool analysis

Recruit with no lag has a significant negative relationship with increased cold pool extent.

Excerpt from New York Bight Fish, Fisheries, and Sand Features: Data Review Volume 1: Literature Synthesis and Gap Analysis:

Natural events are documented for Scup (Morse 1978; Smith and Norcross 1968), Bluefish (Slater et al.2007), and Northern Puffer (Wicklund 1970) in the MAB and NYB as a result of upwelling of cold bottom water, and for Golden Tilefish on the OCS from eastward flow of the Cold Pool (Fisher et al.2014). Such events are difficult to detect and quantify because they are episodic, because they could happen in winter when there are few observers, or because they leave dead animals on the bottom instead of floating (Fisher et al.2014) so that they are only detected incidentally by trawler (e.g., Woodhead (1964)).

library(ecodata)
# Pull cold pool data
cp.ex <- ecodata::cold_pool
# Selecting just the extent and add 1 year lag
cp <- cp.ex %>% filter(Time %in% c(1994:2020), 
              Var == 'extent_index') %>%
  mutate(ext = Value,
         ext_lag1 = lag(ext,1), 
         year = as.numeric(Time))


# Join with recruit estimate 
cp.rec <- dplyr::full_join(recruit, cp, by = join_by(year)) %>%
  dplyr::select(year, recruit_est, ext, ext_lag1) %>% 
  filter(year %in% c(1994:2020))

#no lag
cp.rec %>% 
  ggscatter(x = 'ext', y = 'recruit_est', 
            add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, 
            cor.coef = TRUE, cor.coeff.args = list(method="pearson"),
            add.params=list(color="dodgerblue", fill="lightgray"),
            xlab = "Cold pool extent", ylab = "Recruitment Estimate",
            title="Recruit year")

#one year lag
cp.rec %>% 
  ggscatter(x = 'ext_lag1', y = 'recruit_est', 
            add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, 
            cor.coef = TRUE, cor.coeff.args = list(method="pearson"),
            add.params=list(color="dodgerblue", fill="lightgray"),
            xlab = "Cold pool extent", ylab = "Recruitment Estimate",
            title="Lag 1 year")

Persistence Index: From tech doc: Model_PI measures the duration of the Cold Pool and is estimated using the month when bottom temperature rises above 10C after the Cold Pool is formed each year

Positive values == Longer Negative values == Shorter

Result: Significant negative relationship between recruitment estimate and persistence of cold pool, recruitment declines with increased cold pool persistence.

# Selecting just the persitence index
cp.pi <- cp.ex %>% filter(Time %in% c(1994:2020), 
              Var == 'persistence_index') %>%
  mutate(pers = Value,
         pers_lag1 = lag(pers,1), 
         year = as.numeric(Time))


# Join with recruit estimate 
cp.rec <- dplyr::full_join(recruit, cp.pi, by = join_by(year)) %>%
  dplyr::select(year, recruit_est, pers, pers_lag1) %>% 
  filter(year %in% c(1994:2020))

#no lag

Cold pool index:

From tech doc: The Model_SEI is estimated by the number of cells where bottom temperature remains below 10C for at least 2 months between June and September.

Positive values == colder Negative values == warmer

Result: Linear positive trend is weak and non-signficant.

Shelf water volume

Shelf water volume: A measure of the volume of water bounded inshore of the shelf-slope front. In this analysis, shelf water is defined as all water having salinity <34 psu. The position of the shelf-slope front varies inter-annually with the higher shelf water values indicating the front being pushed further towards the shelf break.

high shv: front pushed towards sbf low shv: front pushed inshore (more slope water on shelf)

Hypothesis: Higher recruitment success correlated with years of higher shelf water volume in spring/summer. These months months may be particularly important as that is when spawning is occurring and the position of the sbf may influence the position of larvae (away from spawning grounds).

Additional variables in this dataset are shelf water temperature and salinity which may also be indicative of habitat conditions.

# Shelf water volume
shlfvol <- read.csv(here::here('data/shelf_water_volume/ShelfWaterVolume_BSB_update.csv'))

# wrangling date info, converting doy to date and month 
yrs <- as.vector(nrow(shlfvol))
shlfvol$Year <- as.character(shlfvol$Year)
for (i in 1:nrow(shlfvol)){
  yrs[i] <- strsplit(shlfvol$Year, ".", fixed = TRUE)[[i]][1]
}
shlfvol$year <- yrs

shlfvol <- shlfvol %>% mutate(date_= as.Date(Year.Day-1, 
                                             origin=paste0(year, "-01-01")), 
                              month= strftime(date_, "%m"), 
                              day=strftime(date_,"%d"), 
                              year = as.integer(year),
                              month = as.numeric(month))  


# Create shw vol by month w/lag
df.lag = shlfvol %>%
  group_by(year,month) %>% 
  summarise(mean_t = mean(ShW.T),
            mean_s = mean(ShW.S),
            mean_v = mean(ShW.Vol))
Shelf Water Volume Analysis
df.join.shlf = dplyr::full_join(recruit, df.lag, by = join_by(year)) %>%
  dplyr::select(year, month, recruit_est, mean_v, mean_t, mean_s) %>%
  tidyr::drop_na() #join with rec dataset
 
df.join.shlf = df.join.shlf %>%
  filter(year %in% c(1998:2020)) %>%
  mutate(
         v_lag12 = lag(mean_v,12),
         t_lag12 = lag(mean_t,12),
         s_lag12 = lag(mean_s,12)) #creating one year lags

df = df.join.shlf %>% 
  mutate(season = case_when(month %in% c(1,2,3) ~ 'winter', 
                            month %in% c(4,5,6) ~ 'spring', 
                            month %in% c(7,8,9) ~ 'summer',

         strong_year_class = case_when(year %in% c(1998,1999,2005,2013,2017) ~ 'yes',
                                  year %in% c(2000,2006,2014,2018) ~ 'year after',
                                  year %in% c(2001:2004,2007:2012,2015:2016,2019:2020) ~ 'no'))


# Plot without lag
df %>% group_by(year, season, strong_year_class) %>% 
  summarize(v = mean(mean_v),
            r = mean(recruit_est)) %>% 
  ggscatter(x = "v", y = "r", 
            add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE,

Gulf-stream index

Gulf stream index was calculated based on method presented by Prez-Hernndez and Joyce (2014). The gulf stream index (GSI) is a measure of the degrees latitude above the average Gulf Stream position based on ocean temperature at 200m (15 C) depth between 55W to 75W.

Positive values indicate a the mean position of the GS is more Northernly, whereas negative values indicate a more Southernly position.

gsi.m <- read.csv(here::here('data/gulf_stream_index/mm_gsi_1954_2022_chen.csv'))


## --- This joins recruit estimate data to GSI data and 
## --- calculates some summary stats(mean, sd, min, max)
df <- dplyr::full_join(recruit, gsi.m %>%
                   group_by(year) %>% 
                   filter(month %in% c(3:8)) %>% 
                   summarise(m.gsi = mean(GSI),
                             sd.gsi = sd(GSI),
                             max.gsi = max(GSI), 
                             min.gsi = min(GSI)), 
                 by = join_by(year)) %>% 
  mutate(pos = ifelse(m.gsi > 0, 'Northerly', 'Southerly'), 
         n.pos = ifelse(m.gsi > 0, 1, 0))
df <- df[-c(51:69),] # this removes rows w/years that don't match 
# (could/should do this before hand in more standardized way - will do later)

# Plot the time series (mean GSI for the months of interest)
# -- Note: here I am looking just at March through August assuming these
# months are the most important to recently spawned individuals 
ggplot(data = df, 
       aes(x = year, y = m.gsi)) +
  geom_line(lwd = 1) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, lty = 2) +
  labs(title = 'Mean GS position anomaly March:August',
       x = 'Year', 
       y = "Gulf stream position anomaly\n") +
theme_bw()

Food availablity

Larval tilefish eat zooplankton, likely calanus. Calanus finmarchicus are a copepod (crustacean) with a one-year life cycle and are an important food source for many commercially important species. Calanus spp. are lipid rich, herbivorous species that eat phytoplankton, diatoms in particular (Hobbs et al.2020).

Diatoms are often represented as microplankton (>20 m), but many species are of the nanoplankton size class (2-20 m), and a smaller few may even overlap with picoplanton size class (<2 m).

Microplankton
micro<-read.csv(here::here('data/phyto_size_class/microplankton_ts_gtf_strata.csv'))

  arrange(year, month) %>%
  mutate(
         micro_12 = lag(weighted_mean_micro,12))
